5000|$|Iomega started {{business}} in Roy, Utah in 1980 (the firm moved its headquarters to San Diego in 2001). For many years, {{the firm was}} a significant name in the data storage industry. Iomega's most famous product, the <b>Zip</b> <b>Drive,</b> was revolutionary as it offered relatively large amounts of storage on easily portable compact cartridges. The original Zip disk's 100MB capacity was a huge improvement over the 1.44MB limitation of floppy disks. The <b>Zip</b> <b>Drive</b> became a common internal and external peripheral for IBM-compatible computers and Macs. However, Zip disk cartridges sometimes failed after a short period, (commonly {{referred to as the}} [...] "click of death"). This problem, combined with competition from CD-RW drives, caused <b>Zip</b> <b>Drive</b> sales to decline dramatically, despite later efforts to introduce larger 250MB and 750MB disk versions. Iomega eventually launched a CD-RW drive.|$|E
